<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Build an LBO Model: 5-Step Framework<=
/h2>



<p>Master these five core steps for any MM LBO analysis. Each step builds u=
pon previous calculations and assumptions, creating an integrated financial=
 model that actually captures deal dynamics and return drivers.</p>



<p>Focus on keeping clean for the sake of your comrades. Broken Excel formu=
las / links absolutely destroy model integrity and create downstream errors=
 that compound throughout the analysis. So Use consistent formatting and co=
lor coding throughout your model=E2=80=94blue for inputs, black for calcula=
tions, green for outputs.</p>


<h3 id=3D"step1" class=3D"wp-block-heading">Step 1: Calculate Entry Valuati=
on</h3>


<p>Enterprise Value equals LTM EBITDA multiplied by Entry Multiple assumpti=
on. This foundational calculation drives literally every subsequent analysi=
s (so don=E2=80=99t screw it up).</p>



<p>Example calculation: $10M EBITDA =C3=97 10.0x =3D $100M Enterprise Value=
</p>



<p>Subtract existing debt and add cash balance to determine Equity Purchase=
 Price. Most MM deals structure on a cash-free, debt-free basis with normal=
ized working capital, simplifying the transaction.</p>



<p>=E2=80=9CGrowing revenue usually <strong>consumes</strong> cash; model =
=CE=94NWC explicitly or you=E2=80=99ll overstate FCF.=E2=80=9D</p>



<pre class=3D"wp-block-code"><code>Equity Purchase Price =3D Enterprise Val=
ue - Net Debt (Total Debt - Cash)
</code></pre>



<p>Cross-check valuation against precedent transactions and trading compara=
bles. Entry multiple assumption significantly impacts returns=E2=80=94a 1.0=
x multiple difference can swing IRR by 400-600 basis points in typical MM s=
tructures.</p>


<h3 id=3D"step2" class=3D"wp-block-heading">Step 2: Create Sources and Uses=
 Table</h3>


<p>Uses side captures every single dollar required to close the transaction=
: purchase price plus transaction fees plus financing costs. Transaction fe=
es typically range 2%-4% of deal value for MM transactions, including inves=
tment banking fees, legal fees, and due diligence costs (lawyers don=E2=80=
=99t work for free, unfortunately).</p>



<p>Sources side shows funding structure: senior debt plus subordinated debt=
 plus sponsor equity. Target 40%-60% equity contribution for stable cash fl=
ow businesses. Higher leverage works for asset-heavy or recession-resistant=
 sectors (but don=E2=80=99t get too aggressive or you=E2=80=99ll regret it =
later).</p>



<pre class=3D"wp-block-code"><code>Sources =3D Uses
Senior Debt + Subordinated Debt + Sponsor Equity =3D Purchase Price + Fees =
+ Financing Costs

Note: Modeled on a cash-free, debt-free basis with normalized NWC; equity i=
s the plug so Sources =3D Uses.</code></pre>



<p>Financing fees represent 2%-3% of total debt amount, covering original i=
ssue discount, legal fees, and arrangement fees. Sponsor equity becomes the=
 plug to balance sources equals uses=E2=80=94this automatic calculation pre=
vents manual errors; everyone loves a good plug.</p>



<pre class=3D"wp-block-code"><code>EV =3D $100M; Net Debt =3D $10M  =E2=86=
=92 Equity Purchase Price =3D $90M
Fees: Transaction $3M; Financing $1M
Uses =3D $90M + $3M + $1M =3D $94M
Sources: Senior $55M; Sub $15M; Sponsor Equity =3D $24M (plug)
Check: $55 + $15 + $24 =3D $94M =E2=9C=93</code></pre>



